Ahoy - It's been a while! I love seeing what you're up to in JJ - you know I used to be the convenor on the Youth Justice Coalition in NSW back in my advocacy days? I also had plenty to do with Just Reinvest and Maragnooka - feels like so long ago!  Anyhoo - I wanted to check in with you from my world of work. Do you know any indigenous orgs who are doing interesting work around de-colonising their structures? Like using more Indigenous decision-making models or processes, or anything fun/interesting? I hoped that the world of ACCO's would evolve into a lot of this, but not sure if they're having to use crappy settler models in order to participate in colonial systems. I know JMB had a lot of thoughts about this back in the day, but hoping for mob that there's more of it going on in practice out in the world, and maybe is just hard to see from the outside? OR, anyone else I can talk to?

Hi Ben, thanks for connecting Our charity is called My Best Life Australia, and we are looking forward to catching up soon to share our plans to introduce our Youth Healthy Relationships programme into sporting clubs across Australia. This is free to anyone interested in presenting our programme and we have volunteers ready to help facilitate it, with degrees in Psychology.  We are also focussing on supplying prefabricated Houses for social housing and have a number of options with designs. Hi Benjamin, Thanks for your post today - it really resonated with me. I work in business development with Martu people in the Western Desert and Kimberley. We work on country developing strong and trusted relationships with people which allows for an approach walking alongside individuals and businesses with the model of business benefiting community. I struggle a lot with the use of stories. Stories are shared with us as a way for the individual or community to communicate their lives, their hopes, visions and experience and it is an ongoing and unfolding process over time.¬† The tension is between sharing stories of the work we do and meeting the needs of the organization I currently work for which is generally a western market type situation and the cultural use of storytelling in developing deep relationships and assisting us in understanding how we as the as the people on the ground can work better. I find the same with images. In the marketing and social media space my current experience is of organizations frequently co opting "storytelling" to allow the use stories and images for our own purposes - often with good intention - but without exploring how we can work together to understand the deeper concept in culture and community and work towards something different. Nothing new here but good to hear you articulate this.¬† I am I look forward to hearing more about your exploration - I think there is space for something new to come through in the¬† marketing space - it already is in film/TV/literature and art and in some ways social media through communities use of FB and other platforms in digital storytelling. Anyway, as with many things it is a great concept to be exploring here. Thanks again for your posts - sharing your experiences and thoughts with others experiencing similar things is helpful. Have a great day. Warm regards Brigitte

Hi Ben,  I hope you are well. I just thought I'd reach out because I have been following you and A Curious Tractor and it seems like we have some shared interests and values.  I also wanted to let you know that my new venture, Everyday Human Rights is delivering an online workshop on the 27th May that could be of interest for you and people in your networks. (I was particularly thinking about the young guy supporting young people in Mt Isa, I'd be more than happy to allocate him one of the free spots if he has the time that day.)  About Everyday Human Rights  We are an independent, non-political human rights educational consultancy passionate about teaching leaders and advocates how to achieve better outcomes for vulnerable people every day through our unique, straightforward solutions based on real-world experience and results. We bring our collective 40 years of deep experience across a range of fields, including human rights education, disability, youth justice, homelessness, policing, domestic violence, mental and women‚Äôs health, gender equality and refugees  About the Workshop The Human Rights in Practice - For Professionals workshop is a 6-hour online unique, practical and experiential workshop that promotes a critical understanding of human rights approach for all service delivery and policy makers in the human services sector.  Who Should Attend: Anyone who works in the social services sector or is looking to build an understanding of human rights in practice in preparation for work in the field. This workshop is relevant to frontline staff, educators, youth workers, policy and project professionals across the NFP sector and government. No prior knowledge required.  What You'll Learn The format is an experiential 6-hour session outlining the key concepts of human rights which includes foundational knowledge, theory and the practical application to your work and your daily life. The series, led by international human rights experts, covers key human rights concepts and how these apply to individuals, organisations and government in the real world.  Cost Standard Registration: $297 per person Early Bird Discount: Save $100 per person when you register before May 16, 2025 Group Discount: $100 off per person when 2+ people register from the same organisation - contact us to receive the code. Sponsored Spots: Two free positions available for eligible participants not currently employed or whose organisation cannot sponsor them  All the details are here: https://events.humanitix.com/human-rights-in-practice-for-professionals-online-workshop  Also, I just saw your call out for youth justice funding information and love the work that you are doing. This workshop would be really relevant to viewing and requesting future funding decisions as well.  Kind regards,  India

CONVERSATION TITLE: North West and Gulf Communities Youth Forum
CONTENT: Sounds good! When I was 16, 17 and 18 I represented Mornington Island at our North West Regional Youth Forum. It was funded by Sports and Rec Qld. Rhonda Bushby from memory led that from Brisbane.   These Forums are working well in Pacifika and we have representation but the vision doesn‚Äôt filter down. A grass roots model is definitely the way to go.   In confidence we have been given the green light by Australian Fashion Week to host a remote Satellite Hub as part of AFW in 2026 and then a First Nations Fashion and Design standalone Festival in 2027 in Sydney.   This is an opportunity to develop our Youth in this space.   Our Team of 3 are also leading the 2026 International Indigenous City of Culture Expo in Sao Paulo.   This year we are doing Couture Fashion Week in Paris and a colab for Carla Zampatti‚Äôs 60th Anniversary.   Imagine if we had a Youth Strategy in this space? We have our own‚Ä¶  Thanks both for responding. It‚Äôs a good stepping stone.

CONVERSATION TITLE: North West and Gulf Communities Youth Forum
CONTENT: Gents good morning. I hope you're both well. I've been following the conversations from a distance re: justice reinvestment and Youth issues in our Region and a lot of the main players aren't even at the Table.   When you look at the Gulf Rugby League Teams as an example - the majority of the Young People 16+ live and breath the lack of opportunities and the opportunities but the "experts" are still having the conversations about us without us. Brodie I was thinking in the future a summit/camp for our Communities led by Community to direct change from our lived experiences, past and present but also guide what that looks like. E.g. We need a simple dry season, wet season approach as well.   All the research has been done from Community Safety Plans, Audits, Strategic Plans, Recommendations etc. If you look at the "Keeping on Country Report" the findings and recommendations are quite simple but no one has taken this on board. I've been doing the majority of work already but the Report has reinforced my thinking and delivery.¬†  If you take a look at how CLCAC run their Ranger Forums - it clearly demonstrates that a Forum of this size and of importance can be held on home soil.  If each Community had their own small Forum and then came together once every year or biannually it could change the narrative. This is how we ran the RL Competition back in the day. The current Battle of the Gulf relates to the Competition but we need a vision beyond that.   The last QRL Remote Rugby League Forum didn't address any of our issues and it won't. Food for thought.

The Family Pathways Program is for families where a young male (12-17 years) is using power and control or violence against the female protective care-giver in the home.  The Family Pathways program provides short-term support around:  Risk and safety responses Advocacy for the female protective care-giver Psycho-education using Break4Change evidenced based model Engagement strategies for adult male/perpetrator in the home (when safe to do so) Active engagement with the Carinity Talera ReNew program which provides longer term therapeutic support for the family.

That is an interesting predicament - I wonder if you could scan through the stories and find some themes and unidentifiable photos to implement?¬† Maybe it's a piece about the WMP and their feelings, what they heard and how it affected their views.¬†  There may also be occasions where you know when the person telling a storie looks and feels ready to do so and there is enough evidence from people on the ground to give confidence. Maybe you go back to the team and explain your options, give clear directions to why you did that and engage in a discussion about the opportunities, risks and creative ways to share stories that will not adversely affect the storyteller.  There are also times where you need to go with your gut and work out yourself what are the risks and opportunties in telling the storey and then make efforts to connect back with an individual. Part of the journey might even be sharing their story so that you can reconnect and find out more ways to help / find out how to fullfil the storytellers opportunity to either say they dont wish to share or they want to share more.  It wont always be a straight line but if you think careful, present your thoughts clearly and when things go wrong own it and learn you will do great.

Empathy Ledger is an exciting project that brings together storytelling, blockchain technology, and social impact. Our platform is designed to empower marginalized individuals by providing them a space to share their narratives, ensuring fair compensation, and connecting them with charities for impactful collaborations.  With our innovative use of blockchain, we prioritize security, transparency, and authenticity in the stories shared on our platform. By tokenizing these stories, we create a system that recognizes and rewards the value of each narrative.  At Empathy Ledger, we believe in the power of storytelling to drive positive change and foster empathy. Our user-centric approach ensures an inclusive and engaging experience for storytellers and users alike.  With a dedicated team that combines expertise in storytelling, blockchain, and social impact, we are committed to building a platform that amplifies marginalized voices, sparks social impact initiatives, and empowers individuals facing adversity.  Investing in Empathy Ledger offers the opportunity to support a project that not only brings financial returns but also leaves a lasting social legacy. Together, let's revolutionize storytelling, empower marginalized individuals, and create a more inclusive and compassionate future.

Hey mate,  Hope you had a good weekend - sorry it took me a bit longer to get back to you, been pretty slammed at work unfortunately.  Overall the sites look great, you've done an awesome job to pull this together, particularly because you've no-code coded it all yourself! It's impressive stuff.  Few comments from me below just doing a pass through for you to consider. Just did a quick 30min run through so please excuse me if I've misunderstood some of it.  Cheers, Reuben   **Experience** - Be clear about who the audiences and who it's for. For example, if there's some content for mentors, some for kids, and some that's suited for both, consider the experience and interactions to suit both. The more targeted the experience (from landing through to content), the higher the engagement is going to be. If you can tailor the UX pathways to be specific for each of the segment groups it'll be easier for each group to be able to complete their goal (goal being accessing the content) - Metadata is a key for SEO. You have heaps of unique content, make sure it's doing as much as it can. I know a lot of the content links off to other providers or content distribution platforms (which is fine as it lightens the load on your servers), but if you can start to progressively tag the previews/content blocks with the meta data which will bump your SEO. - The category/topic filter/sorting is a bit scattered. A quick sorting [UX activity](https://www.nngroup.com/articles/card-sorting-definition/) might help to identify the appropriate mental models for each audience group (kids, mentors, etc). This will help the experience, make it easier for people to find what they need   **Foundation** - The performance is a bit heavy at the moment (on [https://aimelibrary.softr.app/](https://aimelibrary.softr.app/)). It loads a total of 145mb, with some individual gifs taking up to 13mb. While this isn't an issue for us living in metro cities, I suspect a large portion of your target audience may be located in regional towns, some may only have access to 4G mobile data which means the page could take up to 3-5mins to load. I'd look to either pause, or only take smaller, resized or static versions of the previews to lighten this. For context you want to main to have your website load under 20mb. Another way is to have the site load progressively (think social media), where it loads say a small portion, then you have to scroll to the bottom and it loads more later), or to just add pagination and load only say 10 at a time. - To view network and performance (above), just open up chrome, hit F12 > Network and then reload - Site site is currently loading stuff sequentially which is great - content up top comes first, then the previews. What you want to look for here is to make sure that' you're prioritising the key stuff first, and/or that the loading is happening either in parallel, or sequenced in a way that makes sense. - Could add login, but I'd ask the question - what do you need to protect or what's the key reason you need it? Each step/click you ask people to take drops click conversion, so a firewall may actually hinder your goal. I do think there's a conversion play, where you ask just for an email (rather than login) to view - could strike a balance between collecting (and then nurturing) potential mentors, vs usability and seamless access to content. Of course, if you have stuff that would require a login then that makes sense (self-service account stuff) - Accessibility - not sure how differently abled your audience might be, but something to consider is making your site WCAG compliant. This will just mean your site is more open to those who might have more challenges navigating your site (i.e. can't use a mouse, visually impaired, etc). It is a lot of work tho so I would deprioritise this if you don't think it's applicable. - I'd recommend configuring knowledge base platform (i.e. Freskdesk, wix, even notion?). While they'll come at a cost, you'll save heaps of time from trying to build/configure your own version of these in a no-code environment. This will free up your time to spend on more important things (maximising use from your content, focusing on conversion, etc) rather than trying to code it yourself. It will also bring a tonne of features (SMS, automation, reporting, contract management, collaboration, service desk/ticketing, etc) that will take you awhile to build yourself, as well as some cool next level things like AI chat bots (i.e. features that can use your data to auto-build a chatbot for you). At the end of the day, you aren't a tech company, so it would be an ineffective use of your effort and time to spend building custom features (which equates to $). Your specialist skill is your ability to leverage tech knowledge to enable the organisation to run and scale.

More than $200 million has been raised by business, celebrities, philanthropists and the public in support of those affected by the bushfire crisis.  But donating and fundraising in the face of any crisis can be a complex endeavour. Red tape and legal concerns over how funds will be spent have complicated the task of distributing the cash.  As someone in the industry, I want to know more about your experience. How do charities decide what and where resources are needed most? How do you manage public expectations and keep their attention after the headlines vanish and the camera crews pack up? What‚Äôs your advice to those who wish to help?  I‚Äôd love to get your thoughts in a comment on this post, where you‚Äôll find other industry experts chiming in on the subject. I hope to use the insights for the next edition of my newsletter Food For Thought.  Thanks and I look forward to reading your response!  Natalie MacDonald News Editor

I support the brand for Orange Sky, the world's first mobile laundry and showers for people experiencing homelessness. We have quickly scaled to 28 vans across Australia and New Zealand and am now ready to connect the world. We have funders in the US and from there who knows what will happen.  I love your ability to tell powerful stories and your latest video on loneliness perfectly encapsulated Orange Sky's mission to help everyone doing it tough around the world.  What are our options to partner on a piece that better explains homelessness? Australia (and I am sure the remainder of the world) has a very surface level understanding of homelessness. What is the message that allows everyone to see the power of connection and acknowledgment that allows someone doing it tough to see their connection to a community?  At the moment we wash over 8 tonnes of clothes for people experiencing homelessness, but the most important part of that is one hour of genuine and non-judgemental conversation with our volunteers.¬†  How can we together see the power of acknowledgment and humanizing of everyone we meet no matter how they look, act or feel?  Apologies in advance for the rant but the power of your audience is hard to miss.  Hope to hear from you soon. Ben

CONTENT: Hey everyone,   For those of you who don't know me, my name is Andrew Hewitt. I am a drummer with Cerebral Palsy from Sydney, Australia who has been invited to present at the NAMM Show in Anaheim, California in January. I will presenting with Can-Do Musos and representing Australian musicians with a disability.   Can-Do Musos is a global organisation established to provide support and showcase musicians living with a disability. So far we have 200 musicians from 22 countries featured on the website, which is growing all the time.   My role at Can-Do Musos, apart from being a founding member, I do the website, I edit the newsletter, resource new members, and host a weekly online radio show playing only music from Can-Do Musos.   Website is http://www.candomusos.com   By donating to this fundraiser, you can go in the draw for an amazing prize pack from Australian rock legends THE LIVING END courtesty of Pearl, Zildjian, Vic Firth and Remo. A special thanks to Justin at AMS for getting this organised. To donate and go in the draw, simply go to https://ozcrowd.com/campaigns/sydney-wheelchair-drummer-embarks-on-a-journey-to-make-a-difference/?updated=true#.VkKdEL-jT6j   Thanks for your support,   Andrew Hewitt

I've been working as a designer for years and teaching design as well, and the best advice I can give you for branding is "go for it!". Spend the money and get the best branding/logo design that you can, it will portray your business as professional. Your brand is everything - it's not just the logo but the service you are offering as well. Start with a logo and business card for networking and then develop a website. Then create a database of potential clients and you can email them with "specials" (i.e.: In the month of January, you can save $ if you book a shoot etc). If you have at least that as your marketing tool you will start to attract more clients. People want to see your photographic work and a website is the best idea!     Have a look at the below link as it has some interesting tips:    http://www.marketingdonut.co.uk/marketing/marketing-strategy/branding/ten-ways-to-build-a-brand-for-your-small-business    I like the images you took at The Hits and Somejerks gig too :))    Thanks,  Heli.

Hey ‚Ä¶..,    Just a quick note to advise that I have officially forgone my role as Editor of MouthZoff Magazine to pursue a more focused approach to supporting the music industry as a whole.    I have been spending a lot of time researching the music media formula and believe it is time for something distinctive. I understand the need for music news, reviews, gig guides and competitions but think the audience is ready to dig a bit deeper and experience another layer of what goes in the music world.   I also believe there are some amazingly talent individuals writing, taking photos and more generally supporting the music industry craving more investigative journalism, photo documentary pieces and know how to make a living out of their work. Therein lies the inspiration for the birth of wordsimagesmusic.     WordsImagesMusic was created by a photographer (myself) and a writer who want to dig deep into Brisbane‚Äôs (and the world‚Äôs) creativity, who want to go past the here and now, the latest single, the new album, last night‚Äôs show.     WIM intends to work in together with a technology partner to create a community where the people in, on and near the action can tell their stories and build relationships through their creative projects, teaching, learning and collaboration.     There will be a lot more info available over the next few months as the business progresses. For now please continue to send through things of interest, I am ever keen to have a chat about how our new initiative can best support your goals as a band/publicist/band manager/record label etc.     Hope to talk soon.  Ben
